===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|enm|en}} {{m|enm|bal}}, {{m|enm|ball}}, {{m|enm|balle}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{m|ang|*beall}}, {{m|ang|*bealla||round object, ball}} or {{etyl|non|en}} {{m|non|bǫllr||a ball}} (whence the Icelandic {{m|is|böllur||scrotum; penis; a ball}}), both from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{m|gem-pro|*balluz}}, {{m|gem-pro|*ballô||ball}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰoln-||bubble}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{m|ine-pro|*bʰel-||to blow, inflate, swell}}. Cognate with {{cog|osx|ball}}, {{cog|nl|bal}}, {{cog|goh|bal}}, {{m|goh|ballo}} ({{cog|de|Ball||ball}}; {{m|de|Ballen||bale}}). Related forms in Romance are borrowings from Germanic. See also {{l|en|balloon}}, {{l|en|bale}}.
